  <title>Chromatic Tuner</title>

  <p>Audio Recorder includes a chromatic tuner for tuning any instrument. It automatically detects the pitch you're playing and shows how close you are to the nearest note.</p>

  <section id="opening">
    <title>Opening the Tuner</title>
    <p>You can open the tuner in two ways:</p>
    <list>
      <item><p>From the menu: Click the menu button and select <gui>Chromatic Tuner</gui></p></item>
      <item><p>Keyboard shortcut: Press <keyseq><key>Ctrl</key><key>U</key></keyseq></p></item>
    </list>
    <p>The tuner starts listening automatically when you open it.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="using">
    <title>Using the Tuner</title>
    <steps>
      <item><p>Open the tuner (it starts automatically)</p></item>
      <item><p>Play a note on your instrument</p></item>
      <item><p>Watch the display - it shows the detected note, octave, and frequency</p></item>
      <item><p>The indicator bar shows if you're flat (left) or sharp (right)</p></item>
      <item><p>Aim for the center - when the note turns green, you're in tune!</p></item>
    </steps>
  </section>

  <section id="indicators">
    <title>Understanding the Display</title>
    <terms>
      <item>
        <title>Note Display</title>
        <p>Shows the detected note name (C, C#, D, D#, E, F, F#, G, G#, A, A#, B) in large text. Green means in tune, orange means close, red means far off.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <title>Cents Display</title>
        <p>Shows how many cents sharp (+) or flat (-) you are. Â±5 cents is considered in tune.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <title>Pitch Bar</title>
        <p>Visual indicator - center is in tune, left is flat, right is sharp.</p>
      </item>
      <item>
        <title>Status</title>
        <p>Text feedback telling you if you're in tune or which direction to adjust.</p>
      </item>
    </terms>
  </section>

  <section id="tips">
    <title>Tips for Accurate Tuning</title>
    <list>
      <item><p>Play the note cleanly and let it ring</p></item>
      <item><p>Avoid background noise for best detection</p></item>
      <item><p>For bass, low notes may need a moment to stabilize</p></item>
      <item><p>Use harmonics for even more accurate tuning</p></item>
    </list>
  </section>
